# measure of the square center?

big square is area $c^2$.
the triangles are area $(a*b)/2$.

We have the area of the center is
$$
c^2 - 2a*b
=
a^2+b^2-2*a*b
=
(a-b)^2
$$

We are looking for
$$
(a-b) | c \; .
$$

We have
$$
a^2 + b^2 = c^2
$$

$$
a^2 + b^2 = (k(a-b))^2
a^2 + b^2 = k^2a^2 - 2k^2ab + k^2b^2
2k^2ab = (k^2-1)(a^2+b^2)
$$

If we assume $a,b$ coprime, then $ab | k^2-1$, $k^2 | a^2+b^2$.
I believe either
$$
k^2-1 = ab
a^2+b^2 = 2k^2
$$
or
$$
k^2-1 = 2ab
a^2+b^2 = k^2
$$
Only this latter case works, so $a-b=1$.

Multiples of this $a-b=1$ case work as well.

$$
x^2 + (x+1)^2 = y^2
2x^2 + 2x + 1 = y^2 \; .
$$

$$
x=0, y=\pm 1
$$
and
$$
x \gets 3x+2y+1
y \gets 4x+3y+2
$$
$$
x \gets 3x-2y+1
y \gets -4x+3y-2
$$


